  "prompt": "What was Jesus like as a child?",
  "response": "The Bible provides only a few glimpses of Jesus's childhood, primarily in the Gospel of Luke. These passages offer some insight into his character and early life, but they leave much to the imagination.\n\n1. **The Boy Jesus in the Temple (Luke 2:41-52):**\n   - When Jesus was 12 years old, his family traveled to Jerusalem for the Passover feast. On the return journey, Mary and Joseph realized Jesus was not with them and went back to Jerusalem to find him. They discovered him in the temple, sitting among the teachers, listening to them and asking questions. Everyone who heard him was amazed at his understanding and answers.\n   - This story portrays Jesus as precociously wise and deeply engaged in matters of faith and Scripture, even at a young age.\n\n2. **His Obedience (Luke 2:51):**\n   - After this incident, Jesus returned to Nazareth with his parents and was obedient to them. This shows his humility and respect for his earthly family, even though he was aware of his divine mission.\n\n3. **Natural Growth (Luke 2:52):**\n   - The Bible notes that Jesus grew in wisdom, stature, and favor with God and people. This suggests that, like any child, he underwent normal physical, emotional, and spiritual development.\n\nOutside the Bible, some early Christian writings, such as the *Infancy Gospel of Thomas* (not part of the biblical canon), describe miraculous and sometimes mischievous acts by Jesus as a child. However, these accounts are generally considered apocryphal and not historically reliable.\n\nIn summary, the biblical accounts depict Jesus as a thoughtful, wise, and obedient child who was deeply connected to his faith and respected by those around him. His childhood, while mostly undocumented, reflects his unique identity and purpose.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
